s are unmanaged by social conventions or are explicitly primed by elites, status motivations can become drivers of public opinion and political participation. McClendon focuses on the United States and South Africa-two countries that provide tough tests for her arguments while also demonstrating that the arguments apply in different contexts. From debates over redistribution to the mobilization of collective action, Envy in Politics presents the first theoretical and empirical investigation of the connection between status motivations and political behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aEnvyxPolitical aspects. 0aEnvyxSocial aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.23943/9781400889815zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400889815423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400889815/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK